# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: axios-http
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:axios-http/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Requests can be made by passing the relevant config to `axios`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] For convenience, aliases have been provided for all common request methods.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] When using the alias methods `url`, `method`, and `data` properties don't need to be specified in config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Use `Promise.all` instead of these helpers.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Helper functions for dealing with concurrent requests.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] You can create a new instance of axios with a custom config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] The following instance methods are available.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Axios merges the specified config with the instance config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] By default `maxContentLength` and `maxBodyLength` are `-1` (unlimited).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] A malicious or compromised server can return a tiny gzip/deflate/brotli/zstd body that expands to gigabytes and exhaust the Node.js process.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] These config options are available for requests.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Requests default to `GET` when `method` is not set.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] By default, axios decodes `%3A`, `%24`, `%2C` and `%20` back to `:`, `$`, `,` and `+` for readability (the `+` follows the `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` convention for spaces in query strings).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] These characters are valid in a query component under RFC 3986, so the default output is correct, but some backends require strict percent-encoding and reject the readable form.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Axios has experimental HTTP/2 support in the Node.js HTTP adapter.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Support depends on the runtime environment and Node.js version.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Redirects and some adapter behavior may differ from HTTP/1.1.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Options like `httpVersion` and `http2Options` are adapter-specific and may not work the same way in every environment.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If you need HTTP/2, check runtime support or use a custom adapter.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] The response to a request contains the following information.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] When using `catch`, or passing a rejection callback as the second parameter of `then`, read the response from the `error` object.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Axios merges config in this order: library defaults from lib/defaults/index.js, the instance `defaults` property, and the request `config` argument.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Later values take precedence over earlier ones.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Some options are request-specific and are only taken from the request `config`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] `data` is one of those options: axios does not inherit or deep-merge request bodies from global or instance defaults.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If every request needs shared body fields, add them with a request interceptor or `transformRequest`, and scope that logic carefully so sensitive values are not sent to the wrong endpoint.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If you need to remove an interceptor later you can.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] You can also clear all interceptors for requests or responses.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] You can add interceptors to a custom instance of axios.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] When you add request interceptors, they are presumed to be asynchronous by default.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] This can cause a delay in the execution of your axios request when the main thread is blocked (a promise is created under the hood for the interceptor and your request gets put at the bottom of the call stack).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If your request interceptors are synchronous you can add a flag to the options object that will tell axios to run the code synchronously and avoid any delays in request execution.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If you want to execute a particular interceptor based on a runtime check, you can add a `runWhen` function to the options object.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] The request interceptor will not run **if and only if** the return of `runWhen` is `false`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Axios calls the function with the config object (don't forget that you can bind your own arguments to it as well.) This can be handy when you have an asynchronous request interceptor that only needs to run at certain times.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Request and response interceptors use different execution orders.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Request interceptors run in reverse order (LIFO: last in, first out).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Response interceptors run in the order they were added (FIFO: first in, first out).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Read the interceptor tests to see all this in code.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Axios error messages include details that can help you debug the request.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] By default, Axios rejects responses with status codes outside the 2xx range.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Use `validateStatus` to override the default condition (`status >= 200 && status < 300`) and choose which HTTP status codes should reject.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] By default, explicit `validateStatus: undefined` keeps legacy behavior and resolves every response status because `transitional.validateStatusUndefinedResolves` defaults to `true`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Set it to `false` to make explicit `validateStatus: undefined` behave like the option was omitted, so Axios uses the configured/default validator and rejects non-2xx responses by default.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] `validateStatus: null` still accepts every response status.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] If you disable the transitional behavior and intentionally want all statuses to resolve, use `null` or `() => true`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Use `toJSON` to get more information about the HTTP error.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] To avoid logging secrets from `error.config`, pass a `redact` array in the request config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p01] Matching config keys are masked case-insensitively at any depth when `AxiosError#toJSON()` is called.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] You can also cancel a request using a *CancelToken*.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Canceled requests reject with `axios.CanceledError`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] The legacy `axios.Cancel` export is an alias of `axios.CanceledError`, and cancellation errors include `__CANCEL__` for `axios.isCancel` compatibility.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] By default, axios serializes JavaScript objects to `JSON`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] To send data as `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, use the `URLSearchParams` API.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] It works in most browsers and in Node v10 and later.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] For very old browsers, use a polyfill and make sure it patches the global environment.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios automatically serializes the data object to urlencoded format if the content-type header is set to "application/x-www-form-urlencoded".
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] To send data as `multipart/form-data`, pass a FormData instance as the payload.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] You do not need to set the `Content-Type` header.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] For browser, web worker, and React Native `FormData`, leave `Content-Type` unset so the runtime can add the multipart boundary.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] In node.js, when a `FormData` object provides `getHeaders()`, axios copies all returned headers by default for v1 compatibility.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If the `FormData` object is custom or not fully trusted, set `formDataHeaderPolicy: 'content-only'` to copy only `Content-Type` and `Content-Length`, and set any other request headers explicitly with the request `headers` config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Since `v0.27.0`, Axios can serialize an object to FormData if the request `Content-Type` header is set to `multipart/form-data`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] The Node.js build uses the `form-data` polyfill by default.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios supports `postForm`, `putForm`, and `patchForm` as shortcuts for the matching HTTP methods with the `Content-Type` header preset to `multipart/form-data`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios sends all files with the same field name: `files[]`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Pass an HTML Form element as a payload to submit it as `multipart/form-data` content.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Sending `Blobs`/`Files` as JSON (`base64`) is not currently supported.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios can capture request upload and download progress in browsers and Node.js.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Progress events are limited to `3` times per second.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios includes an `AxiosHeaders` class for working with headers through a Map-like API.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] HTTP header names are case-insensitive, but Axios keeps the original header case for style and for servers that incorrectly depend on case.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Directly manipulating the headers object still works, but it is deprecated.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] An `AxiosHeaders` instance can contain several internal value types that control setting and merging.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios gets the final headers object with string values by calling `toJSON`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Header names are case-insensitive, but `AxiosHeaders` keeps the case of the first matching key it sees.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Constructs a new `AxiosHeaders` instance.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If the headers object is a string, Axios parses it as raw HTTP headers.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] The option can also accept a user-defined function that determines whether to overwrite the value.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Empty or whitespace-only header names are ignored.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns the internal value of the header.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] It can take an extra argument to parse the header's value with `RegExp.exec`, matcher function or internal key-value parser.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns `true` if the header is set (has no `undefined` value).
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns `true` if at least one header has been removed.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Unlike the `delete` method matcher, this optional matcher matches the header name rather than the value.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns `true` if at least one header has been cleared.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If the headers object was changed directly, it can have duplicates with the same name but in different cases.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] This method normalizes the headers object by combining duplicate keys into one.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios uses this method internally after calling each interceptor.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Merges the instance with targets into a new `AxiosHeaders` instance.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If the target is a string, Axios parses it as raw HTTP headers.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Resolves all internal header values into a new null prototype object.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Set `asStrings` to true to resolve arrays as a string containing all elements, separated by commas.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns the headers as a CRLF-free HTTP header block, one `name: value` pair per line.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns a new `AxiosHeaders` instance created from the raw headers passed in, or returns the given headers object if it's already an `AxiosHeaders` instance.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Returns a new `AxiosHeaders` instance created by merging the target objects.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios introduced the fetch adapter in `v1.7.0`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] By default, Axios uses it when the `xhr` and `http` adapters are not available in the build or not supported by the environment.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] The adapter supports the same features as the `xhr` adapter, including upload and download progress capturing.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] It also supports response types such as `stream` and `formdata` when the environment supports them.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] When `auth` is omitted, the fetch adapter can read HTTP Basic auth credentials from the request URL, for example `https://user:pass@example.com`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Percent-encoded URL credentials are decoded before the `Authorization` header is generated, and `auth` takes precedence over URL-embedded credentials.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Since `v1.12.0`, you can configure the fetch adapter to use a custom fetch API instead of environment globals.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Pass a custom `fetch` function, `Request`, and `Response` constructors through `env` config.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] This helps in custom environments and app frameworks.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] When using a custom fetch, you may also need to set custom `Request` and `Response` constructors.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If you do not set them, Axios uses the global objects.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If your custom fetch API does not provide these objects and the globals are incompatible with it, pass `null` to disable them inside the fetch adapter.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] A minimal example of setting up Axios for use in a Tauri app with a platform fetch function that ignores CORS policy for requests.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] SvelteKit uses a custom fetch function for server rendering in `load` functions.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] It also uses relative paths, which are incompatible with the standard URL API.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios supports HTTP/2 through the Node.js `http` adapter, introduced in v1.13.0.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Support depends on the runtime environment.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Axios relies on Node.js APIs, so HTTP/2 works in supported Node.js versions but may not work in other environments such as Bun or Deno.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Options like `httpVersion` and `http2Options` are adapter-specific and may not behave the same way in every environment.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Note: HTTP/2 redirects are currently not supported by the HTTP/2 adapter.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] axios depends on a native ES6 Promise implementation to be supported.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If your environment doesn't support ES6 Promises, you can polyfill.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] axios includes TypeScript definitions and a type guard for axios errors.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Because axios publishes an ESM default export and a CJS `module.exports`, TypeScript has a few caveats.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] The recommended setting is `"moduleResolution": "node16"`, which is implied by `"module": "node16"`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] This requires TypeScript 4.7 or greater.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If you use ESM, your settings should be fine.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If you compile TypeScript to CJS and can't use `"moduleResolution": "node 16"`, enable `esModuleInterop`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] If you use TypeScript to type check CJS JavaScript code, your only option is to use `"moduleResolution": "node16"`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] You can use Gitpod, a free online IDE for open source projects, to contribute or run the examples online.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] As a supply-chain hardening measure, this repository ships a project-level `.npmrc` that sets `ignore-scripts=true`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] This blocks npm lifecycle scripts (`preinstall`, `install`, `postinstall`, `prepare`) from any direct or transitive dependency when you run `npm install` or `npm ci` inside the repo.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] See THREATMODEL.md (threat T-S2) for the rationale.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] One consequence: the repository's own `prepare` hook (which installs Husky's git hooks) will **not** run automatically.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Run those two commands once per fresh checkout.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] You do **not** need to re-run them after every subsequent `npm install`.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] Do not remove `ignore-scripts=true` from `.npmrc` to "fix" this.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] That reopens the lifecycle-script attack surface for every other package in the tree.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] All CI workflows already invoke npm with `--ignore-scripts`, so local behaviour matches CI.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] axios is heavily inspired by the $http service in AngularJS.
[src:axios-http/axios-axios-p02] It provides a standalone `$http`-like service for use outside AngularJS.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The **`Promise`** object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] To learn about the way promises work and how you can use them, we advise you to read Using promises first.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A `Promise` is a proxy for a value not necessarily known when the promise is created.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] It allows you to associate handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual success value or failure reason.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This lets asynchronous methods return values like synchronous methods: instead of immediately returning the final value, the asynchronous method returns a *promise* to supply the value at some point in the future.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The *eventual state* of a pending promise can either be *fulfilled* with a value or *rejected* with a reason (error).
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] When either of these options occur, the associated handlers queued up by a promise's `then` method are called.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] If the promise has already been fulfilled or rejected when a corresponding handler is attached, the handler will be called, so there is no race condition between an asynchronous operation completing and its handlers being attached.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A promise is said to be *settled* if it is either fulfilled or rejected, but not pending.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] (Flowchart showing how the Promise state transitions between pending, fulfilled, and rejected via then/catch handlers.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A pending promise can become either fulfilled or rejected.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] If fulfilled, the "on fulfillment" handler, or first parameter of the then() method, is executed and carries out further asynchronous actions.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] You will also hear the term *resolved* used with promises — this means that the promise is settled or "locked-in" to match the eventual state of another promise, and further resolving or rejecting it has no effect.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The States and fates document from the original Promise proposal contains more details about promise terminology.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Colloquially, "resolved" promises are often equivalent to "fulfilled" promises, but as illustrated in "States and fates", resolved promises can be pending or rejected as well.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This promise is already *resolved* at the time when it's created (because the `resolveOuter` is called synchronously), but it is resolved with another promise, and therefore won't be *fulfilled* until 1 second later, when the inner promise fulfills.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] In practice, the "resolution" is often done behind the scenes and not observable, and only its fulfillment or rejection are.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] `Promise` itself has no first-class protocol for cancellation, but you may be able to directly cancel the underlying asynchronous operation, typically using `AbortController`.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The promise methods `then()`, `catch()`, and `finally()` are used to associate further action with a promise that becomes settled.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method takes up to two arguments; the first argument is a callback function for the fulfilled case of the promise, and the second argument is a callback function for the rejected case.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The `catch()` and `finally()` methods call `then()` internally and make error handling less verbose.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] For example, a `catch()` is really just a `then()` without passing the fulfillment handler.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] As these methods return promises, they can be chained.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] We will use the following terminology: *initial promise* is the promise on which `then` is called; *new promise* is the promise returned by `then`.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The two callbacks passed to `then` are called *fulfillment handler* and *rejection handler*, respectively.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The settled state of the initial promise determines which handler to execute.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The completion of the handler determines the settled state of the new promise.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] For example, in the code above, if `myPromise` rejects, `handleRejectedA` will be called, and if `handleRejectedA` completes normally (without throwing or returning a rejected promise), the promise returned by the first `then` will be fulfilled instead of staying rejected.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Therefore, if an error must be handled immediately, but we want to maintain the error state down the chain, we must throw an error of some type in the rejection handler.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] On the other hand, in the absence of an immediate need, we can leave out error handling until the final `catch()` handler.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Each time, JavaScript picks a job from the queue and executes it to completion.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The jobs are defined by the executor of the `Promise()` constructor, the handlers passed to `then`, or any platform API that returns a promise.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The promises in a chain represent the dependency relationship between these jobs.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] When a promise settles, the respective handlers associated with it are added to the back of the job queue.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A promise can participate in more than one chain.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] For the following code, the fulfillment of `promiseA` will cause both `handleFulfilled1` and `handleFulfilled2` to be added to the job queue.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Because `handleFulfilled1` is registered first, it will be invoked first.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] An action can be assigned to an already settled promise.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] In this case, the action is added immediately to the back of the job queue and will be performed when all existing jobs are completed.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Therefore, an action for an already "settled" promise will occur only after the current synchronous code completes and at least one loop-tick has passed.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This guarantees that promise actions are asynchronous.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The JavaScript ecosystem had made multiple Promise implementations long before it became part of the language.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Despite being represented differently internally, at the minimum, all Promise-like objects implement the *Thenable* interface.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A thenable implements the `.then()` method, which is called with two callbacks: one for when the promise is fulfilled, one for when it's rejected.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] To interoperate with the existing Promise implementations, the language allows using thenables in place of promises.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] For example, `Promise.resolve` will not only resolve promises, but also trace thenables.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method is responsible for scheduling the execution of the provided `onFulfilled` and `onRejected` callbacks.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Its semantics, including error handling and asynchronicity, are precisely defined in the Promises/A+ specification, and we shall not repeat them here.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] It's very rare that you need to implement a thenable yourself; even if you are not using native promises, you would probably be using a Promise library such as Bluebird.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **all** of the promises fulfill; rejects when **any** of the promises rejects.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **any** of the promises fulfills; rejects when **all** of the promises reject.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Settles when **any** of the promises settles.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] In other words, fulfills when any of the promises fulfills; rejects when any of the promises rejects.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] All these methods take an iterable of promises (thenables, to be exact) and return a new promise.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] They all support subclassing, which means they can be called on subclasses of `Promise`, and the result will be a promise of the subclass type.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] To do so, the subclass's constructor must implement the same signature as the `Promise()` constructor — accepting a single `executor` function that can be called with the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks as parameters.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The subclass must also have a `resolve` static method that can be called like `Promise.resolve()` to resolve values to promises.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Note that JavaScript is single-threaded by nature, so at a given instant, only one task will be executing, although control can shift between different promises, making execution of the promises appear concurrent.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Parallel execution in JavaScript can only be achieved through worker threads.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The constructor is primarily used to wrap functions that do not already support promises.
