[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A settings object is an environment that provides additional information when JavaScript code is running.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This includes the realm and module map, as well as HTML specific information such as the origin.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] The incumbent settings object is tracked in order to ensure that the browser knows which one to use for a given piece of user code.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] To better picture this, we can take a closer look at how the realm might be an issue.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] A **realm** can be roughly thought of as the global object.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] What is unique about realms is that they hold all of the necessary information to run JavaScript code.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This includes objects like `Array` and `Error`.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] Each settings object has its own "copy" of these and they are not shared.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] That can cause some unexpected behavior in relation to promises.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] In order to get around this, we track something called the **incumbent settings object**.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This represents information specific to the context of the user code responsible for a certain function call.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] To illustrate this a bit further we can take a look at how an `<iframe>` embedded in a document communicates with its host.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] In the above example, the inner text of the `<iframe>` will be updated only if the incumbent settings object is tracked.
[src:axios-http/global-objects-promise] This is because without tracking the incumbent, we may end up using the wrong environment to send the message.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:axios-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:axios-http/intro] This guide will help you get started with axios and make your first API request.
[src:axios-http/intro] If you're new to axios, we recommend starting here.
[src:axios-http/intro] You can use axios in your project in a few different ways.
[src:axios-http/intro] The most common way is to install it from npm and include it in your project.
[src:axios-http/intro] But we also support jsDelivr, unpkg, and more.
[src:axios-http/intro] When using jsDelivr we recommend using the minified version as well as pinning the version number to avoid unexpected changes.
[src:axios-http/intro] If you would like to use the latest version you can do so by dropping the version number.
[src:axios-http/intro] This is strongly discouraged for production use as it can lead to unexpected changes in your application.
[src:axios-http/intro] When using unpkg we recommend using the minified version as well as pinning the version number to avoid unexpected changes.
[src:axios-http/intro] An axios request can be made in as few as two lines of code.
[src:axios-http/intro] Making your first request with axios is very simple.
[src:axios-http/intro] You can make a request to any API by providing the URL and method.
[src:axios-http/intro] axios provides a simple API for making requests.
[src:axios-http/intro] You can use the `axios.get` method to make a GET request, the `axios.post` method to make a POST request, and so on.
[src:axios-http/intro] You can also use the `axios.request` method to make a request with any method.
[src:axios-http/intro] Without a `timeout`, a stalled request can hang indefinitely.
[src:axios-http/intro] See `timeout` in the request config and Error handling for the matching `ECONNABORTED` / `ETIMEDOUT` codes.
[src:axios-http/intro] Now that you've made your first request with axios, you're ready to start exploring the rest of the axios documentation.
[src:axios-http/intro] You can learn more about making requests, handling responses, and using axios in your projects.
[src:axios-http/intro] Check out the rest of the documentation to learn more.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The concept behind `XMLHttpRequest` was conceived in 2000 by the developers of Microsoft Outlook.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The concept was then implemented within the Internet Explorer 5 browser (1999).
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] However, the original syntax did not use the `XMLHttpRequest` identifier.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Instead, the developers used the identifiers `ActiveXObject("Msxml2.XMLHTTP")` and `ActiveXObject("Microsoft.XMLHTTP")`.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] As of Internet Explorer 7 (2006), all browsers support the `XMLHttpRequest` identifier.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The `XMLHttpRequest` identifier is now the *de facto* standard in all the major browsers, including Mozilla's Gecko layout engine (2002), Safari 1.2 (2004) and Opera 8.0 (2005).
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) published a *Working Draft* specification for the `XMLHttpRequest` object on April 5, 2006.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] On February 25, 2008, the W3C published the *Working Draft Level 2* specification.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Level 2 added methods to monitor event progress, allow cross-site requests, and handle byte streams.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] At the end of 2011, the Level 2 specification was absorbed into the original specification.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] At the end of 2012, the WHATWG took over development and maintains a living document using Web IDL.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Aside from these general steps, `XMLHttpRequest` has many options to control how the request is sent and how the response is processed.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Custom header fields can be added to the request to indicate how the server should fulfill it, and data can be uploaded to the server by providing it in the "send" call.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The response can be parsed from the JSON format into a readily usable JavaScript object, or processed gradually as it arrives rather than waiting for the entire text.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The request can be aborted prematurely or set to fail if not completed in a specified amount of time.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] In the early development of the World Wide Web, it was found possible to breach users' security by the use of JavaScript to exchange information from one web site with that from another less reputable one.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] All modern browsers therefore implement a same origin policy that prevents many such attacks, such as cross-site scripting.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] `XMLHttpRequest` data is subject to this security policy, but sometimes web developers want to intentionally circumvent its restrictions.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] This is sometimes due to the legitimate use of subdomains as, for example, making an `XMLHttpRequest` from a page created by `foo.example.com` for information from `bar.example.com` will normally fail.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Various alternatives exist to circumvent this security feature, including using JSONP, Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) or alternatives with plugins such as Flash or Silverlight (both now deprecated).
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Cross-origin XMLHttpRequest is specified in W3C's `XMLHttpRequest` Level 2 specification.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Internet Explorer did not implement CORS until version 10.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The two previous versions (8 and 9) offered similar functionality through the XDomainRequest (XDR) API.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] CORS is now supported by all modern browsers (desktop and mobile).
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The CORS protocol has several restrictions, with two models of support.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The *simple* model does not allow setting custom request headers and omits cookies.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Further, only the HEAD, GET and POST request methods are supported, and POST only allows the following MIME types: "text/plain", "application/x-www-urlencoded" and "multipart/form-data".
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Only "text/plain" was initially supported.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] The other model detects when one of the *non-simple* features are requested and sends a *pre-flight request* to the server to negotiate the feature.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Program flow using asynchronous XHR callbacks can present difficulty with readability and maintenance.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] ECMAScript 2015 (ES6) added the promise construct to simplify asynchronous logic.
[src:axios-http/xmlhttprequest] Browsers have since implemented the alternative `fetch()` interface to achieve the same functionality as XHR using promises instead of callbacks.
